human rights violations have had to cope with painful memories of violence. They have also confronted an official discourse claiming that the Truth and Reconciliation Commission of the 1990s sufficiently addressed past injuries. This book shows victims' attempts to emancipate from their experiences by participating in legal actions, but also by creating new forms of sociality among themselves and in relation to broader South African society. Rita Kesselring's ethnography draws on long-term research with members of the victim support group Khulumani and critical analysis of legal proceedings related to apartheid-era injury. Using juridical intervention as an entry point into the question of subjectivity, Kesselring asks how victimhood is experienced in the everyday for the women and men living on the periphery of Cape Town and in other parts of the country. She argues that the everyday practices of the survivors must be taken up by the state and broader society to allow for inclusive social change in a post-conflict setting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCollective memoryxSouth Africa. 0aCollective memoryzSouth Africa. 0aHuman rightsxSouth Africa. 0aHuman rightszSouth Africa. 0aPost-apartheid eraxSouth Africa. 0aPost-apartheid erazSouth Africa. 0aTransitional justicexSouth Africa. 0aTransitional justicezSouth Africa. 0aVictims of state-sponsored terrorismxSouth Africa. 0aVictims of state-sponsored terrorismzSouth Africa. 4aSouth Africa. 4aapartheid. 4abody. 4aclass action. 4alaw. 4amemory. 4amethodology. 4asocial change. 4atrauma. 4avictimhood. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479983640uhttps://www.degruyter.com